If your uplink uses Holland program Allfix, then the fields "Areadesc" and
"To" are probably missing. It means some useful information is lost.

The meaning of the fileds is in my opinion obvious. If you don't understand
any of them, don't mind. You can live without it.

Fileecho areas are simmilar to echomail areas - you can connect them,
disconnect them, request a list of available areas, etc.

Fileecho processing robot is called "Allfix", which is also the name of
the most common, dinousarur-like shareware fileecho processor.
So you should address all your request to Allfix, in the same way you
address echomail requests to Areafix. See "Downlinks documentation".


Why ChaosFix ?
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ

And why not ?
It is simple, and it has many unique features, like many areas in one
directory, very simple (almost no) configuration... it is cheap...
unregistered versions has no restrictions...

Area types:

Echo                  Every node is allowed to read (receive) files
Free                  Every node is allowed to read and write (send) files
Transit               Same as 'Echo', but files are kept only temporarily.
                      They are stored in TRANSIT\ directory.
Private               Available only for 'Friend' and 'Guest' nodes

Node types:

(all)                 All nodes in PASSWORD.LST file
Guest                 'Guest' node can connect individual 'Private' areas
Friend                'Guest' status in all 'Private' areas
Uplink                TICs from 'Uplink' are allowed to create new areas and
                      'Replace' keyword can be used (but only one file can
                      be replaced when wildcards are used !)

Connection types:

Read Only             Typical for 'Echo' and 'Transit' areas
Read/Write            Typical for 'Free' and 'Private' areas
Sleeping              Temporary disconnected 'Read/Write' area. Sleeping node
                      is alowed to "speak from sleep" - can send files to
                      fileecho.
Inactive              Temporary disconnected 'Read Only' area


